{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492559"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1101"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1101"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.55,0.1,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90776"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1101"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74875"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90776"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman who is otherwise well is being investigated for recurrent urinary infections. She has had three infections in the previous six months and all have responded rapidly to antibiotics. There is no helpful information to be gained from the history and the physical examination is normal. As part of the assessment, an abdominal CT scan is performed (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Adrenal tumour","Pancreatic pseudocyst","Hydatid cyst","Angiomyolipoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a large (13 cm) heterogenous mass sitting adjacent to the stomach, below the spleen and above the left kidney. There are no cystic (fluid-containing) components. Based on probability alone, the most likely diagnosis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst gastrointestinal stromal tumours are relatively common incidental findings, one this size would almost certainly have produced symptoms. Most of these tumours protrude into the gut lumen and as they get larger can produce symptoms related to gastric fullness (early satiety) or bleeding (anaemia). Further down the digestive tract these tumours can cause obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this lesion does appear to be in close approximation to the pancreas, a pseudocyst would have a predominant cystic component. Hydatid cysts can get to this size and have few symptoms - but this lesion is not cystic. Angiolipomatas have a predominantly fatty component and this lesion does not have that appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is very unlikely that this adrenal tumour is in any way related to her recurrent urinary infections and is an incidental finding. \u0027Incidentalomas\u0027 are relatively common finding on CT scanning and most are usually innocent and can be left alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adrenal tumours are relatively common incidental findings on an abdominal CT series."],"references":["O\u0027Sullivan JW, Muntinga T, Grigg S, et al. Prevalence and outcomes of incidental imaging findings: umbrella review.BMJ 2018; 361:k2387."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74875"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1101"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15333"},{"type":"media","id":"15334"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15333"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/76b1a534-c878-49c1-8fdb-61274ac97aed.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/76b1a534-c878-49c1-8fdb-61274ac97aed.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":545}},{"type":"media","id":"15334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15334"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3f90b67f-b7d5-4e1b-beb2-d5ae425307cd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3f90b67f-b7d5-4e1b-beb2-d5ae425307cd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":535,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74875"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T15:53:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T15:53:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1101"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90776"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a gra